1
00:00:30,507 --> 00:00:38,572
[SPEAKER_01]: Hello, everyone, and welcome to Method Happenings, a show foreign about the city of Medford, and I am John Petrella.

2
00:00:39,573 --> 00:00:54,563
[SPEAKER_01]: And the purpose of this program is to give Medford citizens facts and information to help you make informed choices and to discover city services or businesses that you may not have been aware of.

3
00:00:55,463 --> 00:00:57,865
[SPEAKER_01]: And today, we have a very special guest,

4
00:00:58,931 --> 00:01:04,773
[SPEAKER_01]: want to welcome Laura O'Neill, who was from the Meffitt Chamber of Commerce to Meffitt Happenings.

5
00:01:04,853 --> 00:01:08,114
[SPEAKER_01]: Laura, can't thank you enough for coming on the show.

6
00:01:08,174 --> 00:01:09,114
[SPEAKER_01]: We appreciate it.

7
00:01:09,154 --> 00:01:09,895
[SPEAKER_01]: We really do.

8
00:01:11,275 --> 00:01:11,935
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, John.

9
00:01:11,975 --> 00:01:13,016
[SPEAKER_00]: And thanks for having me.

10
00:01:13,536 --> 00:01:14,216
[SPEAKER_01]: Our pleasure.

11
00:01:15,276 --> 00:01:17,057
[SPEAKER_01]: So we get right into the questions here.

12
00:01:17,097 --> 00:01:18,077
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't fool around.

13
00:01:18,837 --> 00:01:24,879
[SPEAKER_01]: And the first question we ask everybody, just some background information on yourself, Laura.

14
00:01:24,919 --> 00:01:26,460
[SPEAKER_01]: Who is Laura O'Neill?

15
00:01:28,672 --> 00:01:28,972
[SPEAKER_00]: Sure.

16
00:01:30,253 --> 00:01:38,479
[SPEAKER_00]: I am a Medford high graduate, which I think comes in handy working for the Medford Chamber of Commerce haven't grown up here.

17
00:01:38,499 --> 00:01:46,344
[SPEAKER_00]: I then left Medford for most of my adult life.

18
00:01:48,615 --> 00:01:54,900
[SPEAKER_00]: I was in New York City, Chicago, and I'm currently back in the area in Reading.

19
00:01:55,441 --> 00:01:57,202
[SPEAKER_00]: And I've been back about 20 years.

20
00:01:58,083 --> 00:02:07,510
[SPEAKER_00]: In between then, I was an attorney for first an insurance company, then a large not-for-profit in New York City.

21
00:02:07,530 --> 00:02:13,455
[SPEAKER_00]: And I was home with my three college kids for a number of years.

22
00:02:14,496 --> 00:02:18,781
[SPEAKER_00]: And when I went back in the workforce, I wanted something different.

23
00:02:20,222 --> 00:02:28,231
[SPEAKER_00]: And I had done a lot with events, public relations, and there was a 10 hour position at the chamber.

24
00:02:29,424 --> 00:02:32,426
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, I signed up for that.

25
00:02:33,406 --> 00:02:35,647
[SPEAKER_00]: And it's now turned into this.

26
00:02:36,128 --> 00:02:43,572
[SPEAKER_00]: And I will add one thing that recently came up when I was giving a talk at the library about MedFed businesses through time.

27
00:02:44,372 --> 00:02:52,596
[SPEAKER_00]: And it dawned on me that really, I wouldn't be here if it wasn't for MedFed businesses, because my parents met at

28
00:02:55,155 --> 00:03:01,257
[SPEAKER_00]: the supermarket that was where PharmaCity was, which was where, yeah.

29
00:03:01,377 --> 00:03:05,599
[SPEAKER_00]: So my mom was the cashier and my father worked there.

30
00:03:06,079 --> 00:03:13,162
[SPEAKER_00]: So I really was, they met at a Medford business that is actually, you know, was diagonal from my office.

31
00:03:13,222 --> 00:03:15,543
[SPEAKER_00]: So I really owe it all to Medford business.

32
00:03:15,703 --> 00:03:17,143
[SPEAKER_00]: Awesome, you came full circle.

33
00:03:17,444 --> 00:03:21,105
[SPEAKER_01]: You're back, you're with the chamber, and that's a good thing.

34
00:03:21,385 --> 00:03:23,346
[SPEAKER_01]: And you've obviously been very busy.

35
00:03:25,077 --> 00:03:35,512
[SPEAKER_01]: All right, so, you know, can you give us a brief overview of, you know, what is the Method Chamber of Congress for people that don't know?

36
00:03:36,972 --> 00:03:38,393
[SPEAKER_01]: which is a majority of people.

37
00:03:38,493 --> 00:03:44,635
[SPEAKER_00]: Because I will say, you know, I have this down to three seconds, I'll give you the minute version.

38
00:03:45,316 --> 00:03:57,141
[SPEAKER_00]: But chambers, you know, there is a national chamber, we have our US Chamber of Commerce, it is an established organization, and then it breaks down to your

39
00:03:57,953 --> 00:04:05,005
[SPEAKER_00]: cities and towns, but the purpose is for businesses to be able to have a voice in their community.

40
00:04:05,606 --> 00:04:09,673
[SPEAKER_00]: Most businesses have specialized

41
00:04:10,813 --> 00:04:21,442
[SPEAKER_00]: groups that they associate with their associations, but the chamber is much broader, and it's for all businesses in a community to advocate on their behalf.

42
00:04:22,103 --> 00:04:27,628
[SPEAKER_00]: And we're different things for different people, you know for a small business we're providing a lot of

43
00:04:28,491 --> 00:04:36,477
[SPEAKER_00]: resources and assistance with their marketing, providing them with people for their accounting, all their professional services.

44
00:04:36,537 --> 00:04:38,598
[SPEAKER_00]: They need a lot more support from the Chamber.

45
00:04:38,618 --> 00:04:50,947
[SPEAKER_00]: And your larger businesses, you know, they're looking at the Chamber on us as a tool to help them find businesses in their community, find the not-for-profits, find the smaller businesses,

46
00:04:51,707 --> 00:04:55,510
[SPEAKER_00]: really become a member of that specific area.

47
00:04:55,830 --> 00:05:05,537
[SPEAKER_00]: So our members use us for different things, but I like to think that we are a crucial person for all of our members.

48
00:05:06,157 --> 00:05:08,559
[SPEAKER_01]: You're an important part of the community is what you are.

49
00:05:08,579 --> 00:05:09,679
[SPEAKER_01]: A very important part.

50
00:05:10,100 --> 00:05:10,300
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

51
